        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>[Mr. Topham suggests (letter, Dec. 5, 1872) that Shakespeare meant that the blush was unseen, not that it was absent.]<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The reference to Topham’s letter was added as a note to the second edition of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2400.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Expression</hi></ref>, edited by <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1222.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Francis Darwin</ref> and published after CD’s death; the note refers to CD’s claim that Shakespeare erred in <hi rend="italic">Romeo and Juliet</hi> when he gave Juliet a speech that implied she did not blush in the dark (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2400.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Expression</hi></ref>, p. 336; <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2401.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Expression</hi> 2d ed.</ref>, p. 355, n. 38). Topham has not been further identified.</note>
        </div>        
            
